\begin{abstract}
% ==============================================================
Traditional educational assessments fail to capture the true ability of learners by presenting identical questions regardless of individual competency levels. This paper presents an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that dynamically evaluates student responses and adjusts question difficulty in real time using a fully LLM-driven pipeline. Building upon the multi-agent competency-building framework of Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024}, we adapt the Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model to a question-based adaptive testing context, reinterpreting its original agents---the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA)---as LLM-powered reasoning modules rather than deterministic formula-driven components. The system is orchestrated through the CrewAI multi-agent framework, deploying three specialized agents powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash: an MCQ Evaluator Agent (implementing SOLMA), a Difficulty Predictor Agent (implementing SOLPA), and an Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent (implementing SOLTA), while domain-aware question generation embodies the LSAA function. A dual-layer architecture ensures UI responsiveness through synchronous rule-based fallback while a background multi-agent pipeline provides richer AI-driven analysis. The system eliminates reliance on pre-calibrated Item Response Theory (IRT) models and static threshold formulas, instead leveraging LLM contextual reasoning to produce transparent, flexible, and explainable adaptive assessments. A design-level analysis demonstrates logical consistency of the agent collaboration pipeline, correctness of the adaptive difficulty rules, and qualitative responsiveness across three cognitive domains: Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
