% ==============================================================
\section{Introduction}
% ==============================================================

Traditional educational assessments adopt a one-size-fits-all model, presenting identical questions to all students regardless of individual competency. High-performing students find such assessments unchallenging, while low-performing students struggle excessively, leading to frustration and disengagement~\cite{weiss2004}. Most existing systems provide generic feedback that hinders accurate competency measurement and limits learning efficiency~\cite{vygotsky1978}. Without continuous adaptation based on performance, assessments remain rigid and unable to reflect the dynamic nature of learning~\cite{mislevy2003}.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) addresses these limitations by dynamically adjusting question difficulty based on ongoing responses~\cite{lord1980}. However, most CAT systems rely on Item Response Theory (IRT), requiring large-scale pre-calibrated item banks and statistically validated parameters~\cite{hambleton1985}. This dependency limits applicability in smaller educational settings, and IRT's probabilistic nature makes question selection difficult to interpret for educators.

Recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) offer an alternative: encoding adaptation logic directly into intelligent agents. LLM-powered agents can reason over correctness and response time holistically, applying natural language adaptation rules for context-aware difficulty decisions.

Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT (Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit) model managed by a Multi-Agent System (MAS) for competency building, introducing specialized agents: the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SOLMA), Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SOLPA), and Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SOLTA). While their framework provides a strong foundation, it primarily targets augmented reality (AR)-based vocational training and relies on deterministic KPI metrics. Our system adapts the APOT model's cyclic stages and agent role separation into a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing environment.

This paper makes the following key contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline powered by Google Gemini~2.5 Flash that maps to the APOT agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA), replacing formula-driven scoring with LLM-native contextual reasoning.
    \item A dual-layer difficulty adaptation architecture combining synchronous rule-based fallback with asynchronous multi-agent LLM analysis.
    \item An LLM-driven dynamic question generation mechanism eliminating dependence on static question banks.
    \item An interpretable, prompt-engineered adaptation mechanism that eliminates IRT pre-calibration while maintaining responsiveness and explainability across three cognitive domains.
\end{enumerate}

% ==============================================================
\section{Related Work}
% ==============================================================

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}
Multi-Agent Systems (MAS) have gained significant attention in educational technology~\cite{wooldridge2009}. Outay~\textit{et~al.}~\cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT model leveraging a MAS architecture with four specialized agents: the \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent), which evaluates the learner's preferred modality; the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), which monitors current performance; the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), which predicts learner potential; and the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent), which determines competency stage transitions. These agents collaboratively compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI). However, their framework targets vocational AR training, limiting applicability to digital question-based contexts~\cite{outay2024}. Our work adapts the APOT philosophy to a question-driven setting, replacing quantitative KPIs with LLM-based reasoning.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing}
CAT has been studied extensively since the 1970s~\cite{weiss2004}. IRT-based CAT systems require large, well-calibrated item banks that are expensive to develop~\cite{hambleton1985}. Our approach replaces IRT with LLM-based agents reasoning over observable performance signals using transparent natural language rules, offering ease of deployment without sacrificing adaptive responsiveness.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}
Recent LLM advances have enabled integration into educational systems for feedback, tutoring, and content creation~\cite{chen2023}. Multi-agent frameworks such as CrewAI and AutoGen~\cite{liang2023} facilitate LLM-augmented agent collaboration. Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956} informs our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard). Unlike prior hybrid systems restricting LLMs to feedback generation, our system delegates the full assessment pipeline---evaluation, difficulty prediction, and adaptation---to LLM agents. Reinforcement learning~\cite{sutton2018} and Bayesian student models~\cite{conati2002} require extensive training data or careful prior specification; our approach requires no training phase and adapts via prompt modification.

