\subsection{Dual-Layer Difficulty Adaptation}
A key architectural innovation decouples UI responsiveness from the heavier multi-agent pipeline:

\textbf{Synchronous Layer (Rule-Based Fallback).} Upon answer submission, the controller immediately applies a deterministic mapping:
\begin{equation}
d_{n+1} = 
\begin{cases}
f_{\uparrow}(d_n) & \text{if answer is correct} \\
f_{\downarrow}(d_n) & \text{if answer is incorrect}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
where $f_{\uparrow}$: Easy$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Hard, Hard$\rightarrow$Hard and $f_{\downarrow}$: Hard$\rightarrow$Medium, Medium$\rightarrow$Easy, Easy$\rightarrow$Easy. The next question is immediately generated at this difficulty and embedded in the JSON response, ensuring sub-second UI updates.

\textbf{Asynchronous Layer (AI Pipeline).} In parallel, a daemon thread executes the full SOLMA$\rightarrow$SOLPA$\rightarrow$SOLTA CrewAI pipeline. The richer AI analysis---predicted difficulty, reasoning, and recommendations---is persisted to \texttt{QuestionPerformance} and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory}, and \texttt{final\_difficulty} is updated. The thread explicitly closes its thread-local Django DB connection in a \texttt{finally} block to prevent connection leaks.

% ==============================================================
\section{Multi-Agent Framework}
% ==============================================================

All agents are powered by Gemini~2.5 Flash via the CrewAI LLM interface with temperature~0.7, executing sequentially with context passed between tasks.

\subsection{SOLMA --- MCQ Evaluator Agent}
The MCQ Evaluator implements the \textbf{SOLMA} (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent) function, corresponding to the APOT \textit{Assess} phase. Just as the original SOLMA monitors a learner's current performance~\cite{outay2024}, our agent monitors the student's immediate response quality. Its role is a strict MCQ examiner: given the question text, correct answer, student's selected answer, and response time, it determines correctness and provides a one-line explanation. Configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False}, it isolates factual judgment from difficulty reasoning. The structured input contains the question, correct answer, student answer, and time taken in seconds. Expected output is a binary correctness verdict with brief justification.

\subsection{SOLPA --- Difficulty Predictor Agent}
The Difficulty Predictor implements the \textbf{SOLPA} (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent) function, corresponding to the \textit{Predict} phase. Where the original SOLPA predicts learner potential~\cite{outay2024}, our agent predicts question difficulty---Easy, Medium, or Hard---based on SOLMA's verdict and response time. The backstory encodes a psychometric heuristic: \textit{``Fast + Correct = Easy question. Slow + Correct = Medium. Wrong = Hard.''}

This mirrors the insight that response time combined with correctness serves as a behavioral proxy for item difficulty~\cite{weiss2004}. No hard-coded time thresholds are imposed; the LLM interprets ``fast'' and ``slow'' contextually, enabling nuanced judgment that rigid numeric boundaries cannot provide. The agent outputs the predicted difficulty level along with its reasoning.

\subsection{SOLTA --- Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent}
The Adaptive Overseer implements the \textbf{SOLTA} (Stage of Learning Transition Agent) function, serving both \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} phases. Where the original SOLTA determines competency stage transitions~\cite{outay2024}, our agent determines difficulty-level transitions. It receives SOLMA and SOLPA outputs as context and produces: (1)~the confirmed current difficulty, and (2)~the recommended next difficulty.

The backstory encodes adaptive rules grounded in the Zone of Proximal Development~\cite{vygotsky1978} and Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956}:

\textbf{Correct answers:} Easy$\rightarrow$Medium (progressive challenge); Medium$\rightarrow$Hard (advance); Hard$\rightarrow$Hard or Medium (maintain mastery).

\textbf{Incorrect answers:} Hard$\rightarrow$Medium (step down); Medium$\rightarrow$Easy (step down); Easy$\rightarrow$Easy (reinforce confidence).

Configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=True}, the agent outputs a structured format parsed line-by-line via keyword matching (\texttt{Questions Difficulty:}, \texttt{Next Question Difficulty:}, \texttt{Reasoning:}, \texttt{Recommendation:}), with ``Medium'' defaults on parsing failure ensuring graceful degradation.

\subsection{LSAA --- Learning Style Assessment Agent}
The \textbf{LSAA} (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function from the APOT model is distributed across two system components: (1)~domain-aware question generation that tailors MCQ content to Reasoning, Aptitude, or Verbal Ability characteristics via topic-parameterized LLM prompts; and (2)~multi-domain competency tracking on the analytics dashboard, computing per-domain accuracy and identifying the weakest domain for targeted feedback.

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}
The three pipeline agents (SOLMA, SOLPA, SOLTA) are assembled into a CrewAI \texttt{Crew} with sequential process execution (\texttt{Process.sequential}), \texttt{memory=False} for stateless per-question operation, and \texttt{max\_rpm=10} for API rate compliance. Task~3 (SOLTA) declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]}, giving the Overseer access to both SOLMA and SOLPA outputs. The information flow is formalized as:
\begin{align}
\text{SOLMA}(q, a_c, a_s, t) &\rightarrow v \in \{\text{Correct}, \text{Incorrect}\} \\
\text{SOLPA}(v, t) &\rightarrow d_{\text{cur}} \in \{E, M, H\} \\
\text{SOLTA}(v, d_{\text{cur}}) &\rightarrow (d_{\text{cur}}', d_{\text{next}})
\end{align}
where $q$ is the question, $a_c$ the correct answer, $a_s$ the student's answer, $t$ the response time, and $d$ the difficulty level. Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline} illustrates the complete three-agent pipeline for a single MCQ response.

