\section{Methodology}
% ==============================================================

\subsection{Input Representation}
For each MCQ response, the system constructs a structured input string passed to the SOLMA agent's task:

\begin{verbatim}
Question: <question text>
Correct Answer: <correct option>
Student Selected Answer: <student option>
Time Taken by Student: <seconds> seconds
\end{verbatim}

This input captures all observable signals for a single question interaction: factual correctness (by comparing answers) and response efficiency (via client-side \texttt{Date.now()} differencing). Together these constitute the behavioral fingerprint that the APOT pipeline reasons over. The default time when the frontend omits it is 30~seconds.

\subsection{Agent Prompt Design}
Each agent's behavior in CrewAI is governed by three natural language fields: \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory}. These function as the system prompt for Gemini, shaping reasoning per task. The \texttt{role} defines the agent's APOT identity, the \texttt{goal} specifies its objective, and the \texttt{backstory} encodes domain heuristics and adaptation rules. For SOLPA, the backstory contains the time-correctness heuristic eliminating IRT parameter estimation. For SOLTA, the backstory encodes the full bidirectional transition table aligned with the Zone of Proximal Development~\cite{vygotsky1978}, ensuring the system keeps students within their optimal challenge zone.

\subsection{Robustness Mechanisms}
The system employs multiple fallback strategies: (1)~API key validation returning canned \texttt{Medium}/\texttt{Medium} results on key failure with reasoning ``Using default difficulty due to API key issue''; (2)~retry logic for transient errors (HTTP~503, 429, 500) up to 3~times with exponential-like backoff of $(attempt+1)\times2$~seconds; (3)~stub fallback questions on total generation failure to prevent test interruption; and (4)~thread-safe DB connection cleanup in background CrewAI threads via explicit \texttt{connection.close()} in \texttt{finally} blocks.

\subsection{Session Management and Test Integrity}
Each session is identified by a UUID (\texttt{assessment\_id}) linking transient session state with durable \texttt{StudentTestResult} records. Status transitions follow a controlled state machine: \texttt{in\_progress}~$\rightarrow$~\texttt{completed} (submit) $\mid$ \texttt{auto\_submitted} (beacon on tab close) $\mid$ \texttt{expired} (exit). A fullscreen enforcement gate blocks the test UI until the student enters fullscreen mode. Tab closure triggers \texttt{navigator.sendBeacon} for automatic submission. A skip-question revisit mechanism defers questions and revisits them after the linear pass completes.

