Key advantages include: (1)~adaptation rules modifiable in natural language without code changes; (2)~contextual nuance in SOLPA's interpretation of ``fast''/``slow'' without hard thresholds; (3)~a full reasoning audit trail supporting APOT explainability goals~\cite{outay2024}; and (4)~zero pre-calibration enabling instant deployment~\cite{hambleton1985}. The primary trade-off is LLM non-determinism, mitigated by structured output parsing, ``Medium'' defaults, and the synchronous rule-based fallback layer.

Additionally, the LLM-driven question generation eliminates a fundamental bottleneck of IRT-based systems: the need for a large, pre-curated, statistically validated item bank. Traditional CAT systems require each item to be calibrated through large-scale pilot testing~\cite{lord1980}, a process that can take months. Our system requires only a topic name and difficulty level to produce an unlimited variety of questions, making it deployable in new domains within minutes rather than months. The trade-off is that generated questions lack the statistical validation of IRT-calibrated items; however, the SOLPA agent's post-hoc difficulty classification provides a form of runtime validation.

\subsection{Competency Analytics}
The system computes a Competency Index (CI) as a recency-weighted average over the ten most recent completed tests:
\begin{equation}
\text{CI} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{\min(n,10)} s_i / i}{\sum_{i=1}^{\min(n,10)} 1/i}
\end{equation}
where $s_i$ is the $i$-th most recent score percentage. Harmonic weighting ensures recent performance has greater influence. Per-domain accuracy (Aptitude, Reasoning, Verbal) and competency banding (Expert~$\geq$85, Advanced~$\geq$70, Intermediate~$\geq$50, Beginner~$<$50) provide multi-dimensional learner profiles. Three persistence models---\texttt{StudentTestResult} (session-level), \texttt{QuestionPerformance} (per-question AI analysis), and \texttt{AdaptiveLearningHistory} (SOLTA difficulty progressions)---form a complete audit trail.

