\section{Conclusion and Future Work}
% ==============================================================

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework~\cite{outay2024} in a fully LLM-driven adaptive testing context. By mapping the APOT agents---SOLMA (Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent), SOLPA (Stage of Learning Prediction Agent), and SOLTA (Stage of Learning Transition Agent)---to three CrewAI agents powered by Gemini~2.5 Flash, the system replaces deterministic scoring and IRT pre-calibration with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning. The LSAA (Learning Style Assessment Agent) function is realized through domain-aware question generation across Reasoning, Aptitude, and Verbal Ability.

The dual-layer architecture---synchronous rule-based fallback for real-time responsiveness with asynchronous multi-agent analysis for rich insights---demonstrates that production-grade adaptive testing can coexist with computationally intensive LLM pipelines. The LLM-driven question generation mechanism further eliminates the traditional bottleneck of pre-curated item bank construction.

Design-level analysis confirms that the three-agent APOT pipeline provides complete transition-space coverage, logically consistent behavior across representative performance scenarios, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision. The system demonstrates that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through simple prompt modification.

Future work will focus on: (1)~conducting user studies to empirically validate LLM-predicted difficulty labels against expert annotations; (2)~extending LSAA with an explicit learning-style profiling agent adapting question format based on learner preferences; (3)~integrating session-level memory for cross-question performance tracking by SOLTA; (4)~exploring prompt optimization to reduce LLM output variability; (5)~comparing LLM-based adaptation against IRT ground truth on standardized item banks; and (6)~deploying for concurrent multi-user sessions with real-time instructor dashboards leveraging the Celery and Redis infrastructure.

